<subSubSection lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="376" pageId="18" pageNumber="375" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1929,2028]" lastBlockId="19.[151,1437,150,825]" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="376" pageId="18" pageNumber="375">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1929,1955]" pageId="18" pageNumber="375">Description.</emphasis>
Male (
<figureCitation box="[431,587,1929,1956]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[172,1432,586,1775]" captionTargetId="figure-136@18.[151,1436,561,1799]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 13. Pectinimura paraliberalis Park &amp; Karisch, sp. nov.: A, Adult, holotype; A1, Labial palpus; A2, Label; B, Male genitalia, GU-3895/Karisch; B1, Aedeagus, in SDEI." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810536" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810536/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="375">Figs. 13A, A</figureCitation>
<figureCitation box="[587,598,1930,1956]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1300,1324]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,345,1276]" captionTargetId="figure-101@1.[151,1436,345,1276]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Topographical map of the region Northwest of Man, Black circles = collecting sites; inserted map: Ivory Coast with marked collecting area (arrow) (Openstreetmap, inserted map: Mapsland, CCA 3.0)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810508" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810508/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="375">1</figureCitation>
). Wingspan 
<quantity box="[744,871,1929,1956]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="18" pageNumber="375" unit="mm" value="14.0" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="12.0">12–16 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis box="[884,945,1929,1955]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="375">Head</emphasis>
: Light yellow dorsally. Antenna about 1.2 times longer than forewing; scape elongated, broadened apically, followed by eight segments of flagellum, covered with long tuft scales. 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[410,426,2001,2015]" fontSize="6" pageId="18" pageNumber="375">nd</superScript>
palpomere of labial palpus triangularly thickened by rough scales, brown dorsally, white ventrally; 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[278,292,150,164]" fontSize="6" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">rd</superScript>
palpomere slender, slightly arched, as long as 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[819,835,150,164]" fontSize="6" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">nd</superScript>
palpomere, Light yellow dorsally, grayish brown ventrally. 
<emphasis box="[223,304,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pale brown. Hind tibia roughly scaled, pale yellow, spurs fuscous dorsally and ventrally. Forewing ground color pale yellowish-brown; with a grayish-brown, with comma-shaped discoidal spot; costa slightly arched in basal third; apex rounded; termen oblique; fringe yellowish-white basally, yellowish-brown to grayish-brown distally. Hind wing ground color grayish brown; discoidal cell and area between M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1081,1089,313,327]" fontSize="6" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">2</subScript>
and CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1197,1205,313,327]" fontSize="6" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">1</subScript>
covered with longer and curled scales; fringe grayish-brown, with a paler basal line.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,150,825]" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">
<emphasis box="[199,364,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[380,528,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[172,1432,586,1775]" captionTargetId="figure-136@18.[151,1436,561,1799]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 13. Pectinimura paraliberalis Park &amp; Karisch, sp. nov.: A, Adult, holotype; A1, Labial palpus; A2, Label; B, Male genitalia, GU-3895/Karisch; B1, Aedeagus, in SDEI." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810536" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810536/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">Figs. 13B, B</figureCitation>
<figureCitation box="[528,539,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1300,1324]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,345,1276]" captionTargetId="figure-101@1.[151,1436,345,1276]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Topographical map of the region Northwest of Man, Black circles = collecting sites; inserted map: Ivory Coast with marked collecting area (arrow) (Openstreetmap, inserted map: Mapsland, CCA 3.0)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810508" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810508/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">1</figureCitation>
): Basal lobes of uncus poorly developed. Basal plate of gnathos triangular, narrowing toward apex. Costal bar connecting tegumen and valva prominently angled, sharply acute medially. Valva broad, strongly, nearly parallel-sided; costa nearly straight; ventral margin with broad expansion medially; sacculus sclerotized, terminated near middle of ventral margin of basal part of valva, connected to a linear band extending to near lower corner of cucullus, bearing long setae; pectinate plate oblique, about 2/3 the width of cucullus, with dense combs. Juxta slitted medially, with a pair of short, triangular lobes medially. Vinculum broad, with round apex. Saccus rounded.Aedeagus stout, as long as valva; cornuti consisting of a sclerotized linear band, strongly bent into U-shape, about 3/5 the length of aedeagus, and a patch of numerous spinules.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,150,825]" box="[199,401,655,681]" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">Female unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,729,690,717]" pageId="19" pageNumber="376" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,150,825]" box="[199,729,690,717]" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,690,716]" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,491,691,717]" name="Ivory Coast" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">Ivory Coast</collectingCountry>
(Montagne District).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1201,727,753]" pageId="19" pageNumber="376" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,150,825]" box="[199,1201,727,753]" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,727,753]" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named after the species name of 
<taxonomicName authority="Diakonoff" authorityName="Diakonoff" authorityYear="1954" box="[714,960,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Pectinimura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="liberalis">
<emphasis box="[714,834,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">P. liberalis</emphasis>
Diakonoff
</taxonomicName>
, due to the similarity.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="376" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,150,825]" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,763,789]" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">Remarks.</emphasis>
The discovery of a 
<taxonomicName box="[556,786,763,789]" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">
<emphasis box="[556,694,763,788]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="376">Pectinimura</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
from Africa is an interesting fact, because the genus is known for the first time from the Afrotropical Region.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
